        <h2 style="color: #000000">
            <span id="History" class="style7">History Of Hospitals</span></h2>
        <div class="style5">
            <span class="style8"><font size="3">Main article: </font></span>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_hospitals" 
                title="History of hospitals"><font size="3"><span class="style8">History of 
            hospitals</span></font></a></div>
        <h3 class="style4">
            <span id="Early_examples" class="style3">Early examples</span></h3>
        <div class="thumb tright">
        </div>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">The earliest documented institutions aiming 
            to provide cures were </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Egypt" title="Ancient Egypt">
            <font size="3">ancient Egyptian</font></a></span> <span class="style1">
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_temple" title="Egyptian temple">
            <font size="3">temples</font></a><font size="3">. In </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title="Ancient Greece">
            <font size="3">ancient Greece</font></a><font size="3">, temples dedicated to 
            the healer-god </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asclepius" 
                title="Asclepius"><font size="3">Asclepius</font></a><font size="3">, known 
            as </font></span><span class="style2">Asclepieia</span><span class="style3"> 
            functioned as centres of medical advice, prognosis, and healing.</span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-8"><span 
                class="style3">[</span>8<span class="style3">]</span></a></sup><span 
                class="style3"> Asclepeia provided carefully controlled spaces conducive to 
            healing and fulfilled several of the requirements of institutions created for 
            healing.</span><sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-9"><span 
                class="style3">[</span>9<span class="style3">]</span></a></sup><span 
                class="style1"><font size="3"> Under his Roman name Æsculapius, he was 
            provided with a temple (291 BC) on an island in the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiber" title="Tiber"><font size="3">Tiber</font></a><font 
                size="3"> in Rome, where similar rites were performed.</font></span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-10"><span 
                class="style3">[10]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">Institutions created specifically to care 
            for the ill also appeared early in </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India" title="India"><font size="3">India</font></a><font 
                size="3">. </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fa_Xian" title="Fa Xian"><font size="3">
            Fa Xian</font></a><font size="3">, a Chinese Buddhist monk who travelled across 
            India ca. 400 CE, recorded in his travelogue that: The heads of the Vaisya 
            [merchant] families in them [all the kingdoms of north India] establish in the 
            cities houses for dispensing charity and medicine. All the poor and destitute in 
            the country, orphans, widowers, and childless men, maimed people and cripples, 
            and all who are diseased, go to those houses, and are provided with every kind 
            of help, and doctors examine their diseases. They get the food and medicines 
            which their cases require, and are made to feel at ease; and when they are 
            better, they go away of themselves.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-11" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-11"><span 
                class="style3">[11]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style3">The earliest surviving encyclopaedia of medicine in 
            Sanskrit is the </span><span class="style2">Carakasamhita</span><span 
                class="style1"><font size="3"> (Compendium of </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caraka" title="Caraka"><font size="3">
            Caraka</font></a><font size="3">). This text, which describes the building of a 
            hospital is dated by Dominik Wujastyk of the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_College_London" 
                title="University College London"><font size="3">University College London</font></a><font 
                size="3"> from the period between 100 BCE and CE150.</font></span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-ucl.ac.uk_12-0" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-ucl.ac.uk-12"><span 
                class="style3">[12]</span></a></sup><span class="style3"> According to 
            Dr.Wujastyk, the description by Fa Xian is one of the earliest accounts of a 
            civic hospital system anywhere in the world and, coupled with Caraka’s 
            description of how a clinic should be equipped, suggests that India may have 
            been the first part of the world to have evolved an organised cosmopolitan 
            system of institutionally-based medical provision.</span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-ucl.ac.uk_12-1" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-ucl.ac.uk-12"><span 
                class="style3">[12]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style3">According to the </span><span class="style2">
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahavamsa" title="Mahavamsa">Mahavamsa</a></span><span 
                class="style1"><font size="3">, the ancient chronicle of Sinhalese royalty, 
            written in the sixth century A.D., King </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pandukabhaya_of_Sri_Lanka" 
                title="Pandukabhaya of Sri Lanka"><font size="3">Pandukabhaya of Sri Lanka</font></a><font 
                size="3"> (reigned 437 BC to 367 BC) had lying-in-homes and hospitals 
            (Sivikasotthi-Sala) built in various parts of the country. This is the earliest 
            documentary evidence we have of institutions specifically dedicated to the care 
            of the sick anywhere in the world.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-13" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-13"><span 
                class="style3">[13]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-14"><span 
                class="style3">[14]</span></a></sup> <span class="style1">
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mihintale" title="Mihintale">
            <font size="3">Mihintale</font></a><font size="3"> Hospital is the oldest in the 
            world.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-15"><span 
                class="style3">[15]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> 
            Ruins of ancient hospitals in </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sri_Lanka" title="Sri Lanka">
            <font size="3">Sri Lanka</font></a><font size="3"> are still in existence in
            </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mihintale" title="Mihintale">
            <font size="3">Mihintale</font></a><font size="3">, </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anuradhapura" title="Anuradhapura">
            <font size="3">Anuradhapura</font></a><font size="3">, and Medirigiriya.</font></span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-16"><span 
                class="style3">[16]</span></a></sup></p>
        <h3 class="style4">
            <span id="Roman_Empire" class="style3">Roman Empire</span></h3>
        <div class="style5">
            <font size="3">Further information: </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byzantine_medicine" 
                title="Byzantine medicine"><font size="3">Byzantine medicine</font></a></div>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">The </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">
            <font size="3">Romans</font></a><font size="3"> constructed buildings called
            </font></span><span class="style2">valetudinaria</span><span class="style3"> for 
            the care of sick slaves, gladiators, and soldiers around 100 B.C., and many were 
            identified by later archaeology. While their existence is considered proven, 
            there is some doubt as to whether they were as widespread as was once thought, 
            as many were identified only according to the layout of building remains, and 
            not by means of surviving records or finds of medical tools.</span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-17"><span 
                class="style3">[17]</span></a></sup></p>
        <div class="thumb tright">
        </div>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">The declaration of </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christianity" title="Christianity">
            <font size="3">Christianity</font></a><font size="3"> as accepted religion in 
            the Roman Empire drove an expansion of the provision of care. Following the
            </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Council_of_Nicaea" 
                title="First Council of Nicaea"><font size="3">First Council of Nicaea</font></a><font 
                size="3"> in 325 A.D. construction of a hospital in every </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathedral" title="Cathedral">
            <font size="3">cathedral</font></a><font size="3"> town was begun. Among the 
            earliest were those built by the physician </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampson_the_Hospitable" 
                title="Sampson the Hospitable"><font size="3">Saint Sampson</font></a><font 
                size="3"> in </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constantinople" 
                title="Constantinople"><font size="3">Constantinople</font></a><font 
                size="3"> and by </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basil_of_Caesarea" 
                title="Basil of Caesarea"><font size="3">Basil, bishop of Caesarea</font></a><font 
                size="3"> in modern-day Turkey. Called the &quot;Basilias&quot;, the latter resembled 
            a city and included housing for doctors and nurses and separate buildings for 
            various classes of patients.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-18" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-18"><span 
                class="style3">[18]</span></a></sup><span class="style3"> There was a 
            separate section for lepers.</span><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-19"><span 
                class="style3">[19]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> 
            Some hospitals maintained libraries and training programmes, and doctors 
            compiled their medical and pharmacological studies in manuscripts. Thus 
            in-patient medical care in the sense of what we today consider a hospital, was 
            an invention driven by </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian" 
                title="Christian"><font size="3">Christian</font></a><font size="3"> mercy 
            and </font><a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byzantine" 
                title="Byzantine"><font size="3">Byzantine</font></a><font size="3"> 
            innovation.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-20"><span 
                class="style3">[20]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> 
            Byzantine hospital staff included the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chief_Physician" title="Chief Physician">
            <font size="3">Chief Physician</font></a><font size="3"> (archiatroi), 
            professional nurses (hypourgoi) and the orderlies (hyperetai). By the twelfth 
            century, Constantinople had two well-organised hospitals, staffed by doctors who 
            were both male and female. Facilities included systematic treatment procedures 
            and specialised wards for various diseases.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-21" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-21"><span 
                class="style3">[21]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">A hospital and medical training centre also 
            existed at </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gundeshapur" 
                title="Gundeshapur"><font size="3">Gundeshapur</font></a><font size="3">. 
            The city of </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gundeshapur" 
                title="Gundeshapur"><font size="3">Gundeshapur</font></a><font size="3"> was 
            founded in 271 CE by the </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sasanian" title="Sasanian">
            <font size="3">Sasanian</font></a><font size="3"> king </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shapur_I" title="Shapur I"><font size="3">
            Shapur I</font></a><font size="3">. It was one of the major cities in </font>
            <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khuzestan" 
                title="Khuzestan"><font size="3">Khuzestan</font></a><font size="3"> 
            province of the Persian empire in what is today </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iran" title="Iran"><font size="3">Iran</font></a><font 
                size="3">. A large percentage of the population were </font>
            <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syriac" 
                title="Syriac"><font size="3">Syriacs</font></a><font size="3">, most of 
            whom were Christians. Under the rule of </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khusraw_I" title="Khusraw I">
            <font size="3">Khusraw I</font></a><font size="3">, refuge was granted to </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greece" title="Greece"><font size="3">
            Greek</font></a></span> <span class="style1"><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nestorian_Christian" 
                title="Nestorian Christian"><font size="3">Nestorian Christian</font></a><font 
                size="3"> philosophers including the scholars of the Persian School of
            </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edessa,_Mesopotamia" 
                title="Edessa, Mesopotamia"><font size="3">Edessa</font></a><font size="3"> 
            (</font><a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urfa" 
                title="Urfa"><font size="3">Urfa</font></a><font size="3">)(also called the 
            Academy of </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Athens" title="Athens">
            <font size="3">Athens</font></a><font size="3">), a </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian" title="Christian">
            <font size="3">Christian</font></a><font size="3"> theological and medical 
            university. These scholars made their way to Gundeshapur in 529 following the 
            closing of the academy by Emperor Justinian. They were engaged in medical 
            sciences and initiated the first translation projects of medical texts.</font></span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-22"><span 
                class="style3">[22]</span></a></sup><span class="style3"> The arrival of 
            these medical practitioners from Edessa marks the beginning of the hospital and 
            medical centre at Gundeshapur.</span><sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-23"><span 
                class="style3">[23]</span></a></sup><span class="style3"> It included a 
            medical school and hospital (bimaristan), a pharmacology laboratory, a 
            translation house, a library and an observatory.</span><sup id="cite_ref-24" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-24"><span 
                class="style3">[24]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> 
            Indian doctors also contributed to the school at Gundeshapur, most notably the 
            medical researcher Mankah. Later after Islamic invasion, the writings of Mankah 
            and of the Indian doctor Sustura were translated into Arabic at </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baghdad" title="Baghdad"><font size="3">
            Baghdad</font></a></span>.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-25"><span 
                class="style3">[25]</span></a></sup></p>
        <h3 class="style4">
            <span id="Medieval_Islamic_world" class="style3">Medieval Islamic world</span></h3>
        <div class="style5">
            <font size="3">Main article: </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medicine_in_medieval_Islam" 
                title="Medicine in medieval Islam"><font size="3">Medicine in medieval Islam</font></a></div>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">The first prominent </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bimaristan" title="Bimaristan">
            <font size="3">Islamic hospital</font></a><font size="3"> was founded in </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damascus" title="Damascus"><font size="3">
            Damascus</font></a><font size="3">, </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syria" title="Syria"><font size="3">Syria</font></a><font 
                size="3"> in around 707 with assistance from Christians.</font></span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-26"><span 
                class="style3">[26]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> 
            However most agree that the establishment at </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baghdad" title="Baghdad"><font size="3">
            Baghdad</font></a><font size="3"> was the most influential; it opened during the
            </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abbasid_Caliphate" 
                title="Abbasid Caliphate"><font size="3">Abbasid Caliphate</font></a><font 
                size="3"> of </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harun_al-Rashid" 
                title="Harun al-Rashid"><font size="3">Harun al-Rashid</font></a><font 
                size="3"> in the 8th century.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-Glubb_27-0" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-Glubb-27"><span 
                class="style3">[27]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> The
            </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bimaristan" title="Bimaristan">
            <font size="3">bimaristan</font></a><font size="3"> (medical school) and bayt 
            al-hikmah (</font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House_of_wisdom" title="House of wisdom"><font 
                size="3">house of wisdom</font></a><font size="3">) were established by 
            professors and graduates from Gundeshapur and was first headed by the Christian 
            physician </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jabril_ibn_Bukhtishu" 
                title="Jabril ibn Bukhtishu"><font size="3">Jibrael ibn Bukhtishu</font></a><font 
                size="3"> from </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gundeshapur" 
                title="Gundeshapur"><font size="3">Gundeshapur</font></a><font size="3"> and 
            later by Islamic physicians.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-28" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-28"><span 
                class="style3">[28]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style3">In the ninth and tenth centuries the hospital in Baghdad 
            employed twenty-five staff physicians and had separate wards for different 
            conditions.</span><sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-29"><span 
                class="style3">[29]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> The 
            Al-Qairawan hospital and mosque, in </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tunisia" title="Tunisia"><font size="3">
            Tunisia</font></a><font size="3">, were built under the </font>
            <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aghlabid" 
                title="Aghlabid"><font size="3">Aghlabid</font></a><font size="3"> rule in 
            830 and was simple, but adequately equipped with halls organised into waiting 
            rooms, a </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mosque" title="Mosque">
            <font size="3">mosque</font></a><font size="3">, and a special bath. The first 
            hospital in Egypt was opened in 872 and thereafter public hospitals sprang up 
            all over the empire from </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Andalus" title="Al-Andalus">
            <font size="3">Islamic Spain</font></a><font size="3"> and the </font>
            <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maghrib" 
                title="Maghrib"><font size="3">Maghrib</font></a><font size="3"> to </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Iran" title="History of Iran">
            <font size="3">Persia</font></a><font size="3">. The first Islamic </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychiatric_hospital" 
                title="Psychiatric hospital"><font size="3">psychiatric hospital</font></a><font 
                size="3"> opened in </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baghdad" 
                title="Baghdad"><font size="3">Baghdad</font></a><font size="3"> in 705. 
            Many other Islamic hospitals also often had their own wards </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychology_in_medieval_Islam" 
                title="Psychology in medieval Islam"><font size="3">dedicated to mental 
            health</font></a></span>.<sup id="cite_ref-Medicine_And_Health_30-0" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-Medicine_And_Health-30"><span 
                class="style3">[30]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style3">In contrast to medieval Europe, medical school under Islam 
            did not have faculties and did not develop a system of academic evaluation and 
            certification</span><sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-31"><span 
                class="style3">[31]</span></a></sup></p>
        <h3 class="style4">
            <span id="Medieval_Europe" class="style3">Medieval Europe</span></h3>
        <div class="thumb tright">
        </div>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">Medieval hospitals in Europe followed a 
            similar pattern to the </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byzantine" title="Byzantine">
            <font size="3">Byzantine</font></a><font size="3">. They were religious 
            communities, with care provided by </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monk" title="Monk"><font size="3">monks</font></a><font 
                size="3"> and </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nun" title="Nun">
            <font size="3">nuns</font></a><font size="3">. (An old French term for hospital 
            is </font></span><span class="style2">hôtel-Dieu</span><span class="style1"><font 
                size="3">, &quot;hostel of God.&quot;) Some were attached to monasteries; others were 
            independent and had their own endowments, usually of property, which provided 
            income for their support. Some hospitals were multi-functional while others were 
            founded for specific purposes such as leper hospitals, or as refuges for the 
            poor, or for </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pilgrim" 
                title="Pilgrim"><font size="3">pilgrims</font></a><font size="3">: not all 
            cared for the sick. The first Spanish hospital, founded by the Catholic </font>
            <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visigoth" 
                title="Visigoth"><font size="3">Visigoth</font></a><font size="3"> bishop
            </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masona" title="Masona">
            <font size="3">Masona</font></a><font size="3"> in 580AD at </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mérida,_Spain" title="Mérida, Spain">
            <font size="3">Mérida</font></a><font size="3">, was a </font></span>
            <span class="style2"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xenodochium" 
                title="Xenodochium">xenodochium</a></span><span class="style1"><font 
                size="3"> designed as an inn for travellers (mostly pilgrims to the shrine 
            of </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eulalia_of_Mérida" 
                title="Eulalia of Mérida"><font size="3">Eulalia of Mérida</font></a><font 
                size="3">) as well as a hospital for citizens and local farmers. The 
            hospital&#39;s endowment consisted of farms to feed its patients and guests.</font></span></p>
        <div class="thumb tleft">
        </div>
        <p class="style5">
            <font size="3">The </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ospedale_Maggiore" 
                title="Ospedale Maggiore"><font size="3">Ospedale Maggiore</font></a><font 
                size="3">, traditionally named Ca&#39; Granda (i.e. Big House), in </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milan" title="Milan"><font size="3">Milan</font></a><font 
                size="3">, northern Italy, was constructed to house one of the first 
            community hospitals, the largest such undertaking of the fifteenth century. 
            Commissioned by Francesco Sforza in 1456 and designed by Antonio Filarete it is 
            among the first examples of Renaissance architecture in Lombardy.</font></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style3">The Normans brought their hospital system along when they 
            conquered England in 1066. By merging with traditional land-tenure and customs, 
            the new charitable houses became popular and were distinct from both English 
            monasteries and French hospitals. They dispensed alms and some medicine, and 
            were generously endowed by the nobility and gentry who counted on them for 
            spiritual rewards after death.</span><sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-32"><span 
                class="style3">[32]</span></a></sup></p>
        <h3 class="style4">
            <span id="Early_modern_and_Enlightenment_Europe" class="style3">Early modern and 
            Enlightenment Europe</span></h3>
        <p class="style5">
            <font size="3">In Europe the medieval concept of Christian care evolved during 
            the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries into a secular one. After the </font>
            <a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dissolution_of_the_monasteries" 
                title="Dissolution of the monasteries"><font size="3">dissolution of the 
            monasteries</font></a><font size="3"> in 1540 by King </font>
            <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_VIII" 
                title="Henry VIII"><font size="3">Henry VIII</font></a><font size="3"> the 
            church abruptly ceased to be the supporter of hospitals, and only by direct 
            petition from the citizens of </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London" title="London"><font size="3">
            London</font></a><font size="3">, were the hospitals </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Bartholomew's_Hospital" 
                title="St Bartholomew's Hospital"><font size="3">St Bartholomew&#39;s</font></a><font 
                size="3">, </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Thomas's_Hospital" 
                title="St Thomas's Hospital"><font size="3">St Thomas&#39;s</font></a><font 
                size="3"> and </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bethlem_Royal_Hospital" 
                title="Bethlem Royal Hospital"><font size="3">St Mary of Bethlehem&#39;s</font></a><font 
                size="3"> (Bedlam) endowed directly by the crown; this was the first 
            instance of secular support being provided for medical institutions.</font></p>
        <div class="thumb tleft">
        </div>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">The voluntary hospital movement began in the 
            early 18th century, with hospitals being founded in London by the 1710s and 20s, 
            including </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westminster_Hospital" 
                title="Westminster Hospital"><font size="3">Westminster Hospital</font></a><font 
                size="3"> (1719) promoted by the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Private_bank" title="Private bank">
            <font size="3">private bank</font></a></span> <span class="style1">
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._Hoare_&_Co" title="C. Hoare &amp; Co">
            <font size="3">C. Hoare &amp; Co</font></a><font size="3"> and </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guy's_Hospital" title="Guy's Hospital">
            <font size="3">Guy&#39;s Hospital</font></a><font size="3"> (1724) funded from the 
            bequest of the wealthy merchant, </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Guy" title="Thomas Guy">
            <font size="3">Thomas Guy</font></a><font size="3">. Other hospitals sprang up 
            in London and other British cities over the century, many paid for by private 
            subscriptions. St. Bartholomew&#39;s opened in London in 1730, and the London 
            Hospital in 1752.</font></span></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">These hospitals represented a turning point 
            in the function of the institution; they began to evolve from being basic places 
            of care for the sick to becoming centres of medical innovation and discovery and 
            the principle place for the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_education" 
                title="Medical education"><font size="3">education</font></a><font size="3"> 
            and training of prospective practitioners. Some of the era&#39;s greatest </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surgeon" title="Surgeon"><font size="3">
            surgeons</font></a><font size="3"> and doctors worked and passed on their 
            knowledge at the hospitals.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-33" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-33"><span 
                class="style3">[33]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> 
            They also changed from being mere homes of refuge to being complex institutions 
            for the provision of medicine and care for sick. The </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charité" title="Charité"><font size="3">
            Charité</font></a><font size="3"> was founded in Berlin in 1710 by King </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederick_I_of_Prussia" 
                title="Frederick I of Prussia"><font size="3">Frederick I of Prussia</font></a><font 
                size="3"> as a response to an outbreak of plague.</font></span></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">The concept of voluntary hospitals also 
            spread to </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colonial_America" title="Colonial America">
            <font size="3">Colonial America</font></a><font size="3">; the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pennsylvania_Hospital" 
                title="Pennsylvania Hospital"><font size="3">Pennsylvania Hospital</font></a><font 
                size="3"> opened in 1752, </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_Hospital" 
                title="New York Hospital"><font size="3">New York Hospital</font></a><font 
                size="3"> in 1771, and </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_General_Hospital" 
                title="Massachusetts General Hospital"><font size="3">Massachusetts General 
            Hospital</font></a><font size="3"> in 1811. When the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vienna_General_Hospital" 
                title="Vienna General Hospital"><font size="3">Vienna General Hospital</font></a><font 
                size="3"> opened in 1784 (instantly becoming the world&#39;s largest hospital), 
            physicians acquired a new facility that gradually developed into one of the most 
            important research centres.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-34" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-34"><span 
                class="style3">[34]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">Another </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Age_of_Enlightenment" 
                title="Age of Enlightenment"><font size="3">Enlightenment</font></a><font 
                size="3"> era charitable innovation was the dispensary; these would issue 
            the poor with </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medicine" 
                title="Medicine"><font size="3">medicines</font></a><font size="3"> free of 
            charge. The London Dispensary opened its doors in 1696 as the first such clinic 
            in the </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Empire" 
                title="British Empire"><font size="3">British Empire</font></a><font 
                size="3">. The idea was slow to catch on until the 1770s, when many such 
            organisations began to appear, including the </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_Dispensary_of_Edinburgh" 
                title="Public Dispensary of Edinburgh"><font size="3">Public Dispensary of 
            Edinburgh</font></a><font size="3"> (1776), the </font><a class="new" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Metropolitan_Dispensary_and_Charitable_Fund&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" 
                title="Metropolitan Dispensary and Charitable Fund (page does not exist)">
            <font size="3">Metropolitan Dispensary and Charitable Fund</font></a><font 
                size="3"> (1779) and the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finsbury_Dispensary" 
                title="Finsbury Dispensary"><font size="3">Finsbury Dispensary</font></a><font 
                size="3"> (1780). Dispensaries were also opened in New York 1771, 
            Philadelphia 1786, and Boston 1796.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-35" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-35"><span 
                class="style3">[35]</span></a></sup></p>
        <h3 class="style4">
            <span id="19th_century" class="style3">19th century</span></h3>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">English physician </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Percival" title="Thomas Percival">
            <font size="3">Thomas Percival</font></a><font size="3"> (1740-1804) wrote a 
            comprehensive system of medical conduct, </font></span><span class="style2">
            &#39;Medical Ethics, or a Code of Institutes and Precepts, Adapted to the 
            Professional Conduct of Physicians and Surgeons</span><span class="style3"> 
            (1803) that set the standard for many textbooks.</span><sup id="cite_ref-36" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-36"><span 
                class="style3">[36]</span></a></sup></p>
        <div class="thumb tright">
        </div>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">In the mid 19th century, hospitals and the 
            medical profession became more professionalised, with a reorganisation of 
            hospital management along more bureaucratic and administrative lines. The </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apothecaries_Act_1815" 
                title="Apothecaries Act 1815"><font size="3">Apothecaries Act 1815</font></a><font 
                size="3"> made it compulsory for medical students to practise for at least 
            half a year at a hospital as part of their training.</font></span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-37"><span 
                class="style3">[37]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1">
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florence_Nightingale" 
                title="Florence Nightingale"><font size="3">Florence Nightingale</font></a><font 
                size="3"> pioneered the modern profession of </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nursing" title="Nursing"><font size="3">
            nursing</font></a><font size="3"> during the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crimean_War" title="Crimean War">
            <font size="3">Crimean War</font></a><font size="3"> when she set an example of 
            compassion, commitment to patient care and diligent and thoughtful hospital 
            administration. The first official nurses’ training programme, the Nightingale 
            School for Nurses, was opened in 1860, with the mission of training nurses to 
            work in hospitals, to work with the poor and to teach.</font></span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-38"><span 
                class="style3">[38]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">Nightingale was instrumental in reforming 
            the nature of the hospital, by improving </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanitation" title="Sanitation">
            <font size="3">sanitation</font></a><font size="3"> standards and changing the 
            image of the hospital from a place the sick would go to die, to an institution 
            devoted to recuperation and healing. She also emphasised the importance of
            </font><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title="Statistics">
            <font size="3">statistical measurement</font></a><font size="3"> for determining 
            the success rate of a given intervention and pushed for </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_administration" 
                title="Public administration"><font size="3">administrative reform</font></a><font 
                size="3"> at hospitals.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-39" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-39"><span 
                class="style3">[39]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style5">
            <font size="3">By the late 19th century, the modern hospital was beginning to 
            take shape with a proliferation of a variety of public and private hospital 
            systems. By the 1870s, hospitals had more than trebled their original average 
            intake of 3,000 patients. In continental Europe the new hospitals generally were 
            built and run from public funds. The </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Health_Service" 
                title="National Health Service"><font size="3">National Health Service</font></a><font 
                size="3">, the principle provider of health care in the United Kingdom, was 
            founded in 1948.</font></p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style1"><font size="3">During the nineteenth century, the Second 
            Viennese Medical School emerged with the contributions of physicians such as
            </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Freiherr_von_Rokitansky" 
                title="Carl Freiherr von Rokitansky"><font size="3">Carl Freiherr von 
            Rokitansky</font></a><font size="3">, </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josef_Škoda" title="Josef Škoda">
            <font size="3">Josef Škoda</font></a><font size="3">, </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferdinand_Ritter_von_Hebra" 
                title="Ferdinand Ritter von Hebra"><font size="3">Ferdinand Ritter von Hebra</font></a><font 
                size="3">, and </font><a class="mw-redirect" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ignaz_Philipp_Semmelweis" 
                title="Ignaz Philipp Semmelweis"><font size="3">Ignaz Philipp Semmelweis</font></a><font 
                size="3">. Basic medical science expanded and specialisation advanced. 
            Furthermore, the first dermatology, eye, as well as ear, nose, and throat 
            clinics in the world were founded in </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vienna" title="Vienna"><font size="3">
            Vienna</font></a><font size="3">, being considered as the birth of specialised 
            medicine.</font></span><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-40"><span 
                class="style3">[40]</span></a></sup></p>
        <h2 class="style4">
            <span id="Criticism" class="style3">Criticism</span></h2>
        <p class="style6">
            While hospitals, by concentrating equipment, skilled staff and other resources 
            in one place, clearly provide important help to patients with serious or rare 
            health problems, hospitals also are criticised for a number of faults, some of 
            which are endemic to the system, others which develop from what some consider 
            wrong approaches to health care.</p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style3">One criticism often voiced is the &#39;industrialised&#39; nature 
            of care, with constantly shifting treatment staff, which dehumanises the patient 
            and prevents more effective care as doctors and nurses rarely are intimately 
            familiar with the patient. The high working pressures often put on the staff can 
            sometimes exacerbate such rushed and impersonal treatment. The architecture and 
            setup of modern hospitals often is voiced as a contributing factor to the 
            feelings of faceless treatment many people complain about.</span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-41"><span 
                class="style3">[41]</span></a></sup></p>
        <h2 class="style4">
            <span id="Funding" class="style3">Funding</span></h2>
        <p class="style6">
            In the modern era, hospitals are, broadly, either funded by the government of 
            the country in which they are situated, or survive financially by competing in 
            the private sector (a number of hospitals also are still supported by the 
            historical type of charitable or religious associations).</p>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style3">In the United Kingdom for example, a relatively 
            comprehensive, &quot;free at the point of delivery&quot; health care system exists, funded 
            by the state. Hospital care is thus relatively easily available to all legal 
            residents, although free emergency care is available to anyone, regardless of 
            nationality or status. As hospitals prioritise their limited resources, there is 
            a tendency for &#39;waiting lists&#39; for non-crucial treatment in countries with such 
            systems, as opposed to letting higher-payers get treated first, so sometimes 
            those who can afford it take out private health care to get treatment more 
            quickly.</span><sup id="cite_ref-GROW_42-0" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-GROW-42"><span 
                class="style3">[42]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> On 
            the other hand, some countries, including the USA, have in the twentieth century 
            introduced a private-based, </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business" title="Business"><font size="3">
            for-profit</font></a><font size="3">-approach to providing hospital care, with 
            few state-money supported &#39;charity&#39; hospitals remaining today.</font></span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-USATODAY_43-0" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-USATODAY-43"><span 
                class="style3">[43]</span></a></sup><span class="style1"><font size="3"> 
            Where for-profit hospitals in such countries admit uninsured patients in 
            emergency situations (such as during and after </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurricane_Katrina" 
                title="Hurricane Katrina"><font size="3">Hurricane Katrina</font></a><font 
                size="3"> in the USA), they incur direct financial losses,</font></span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-USATODAY_43-1" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-USATODAY-43"><span 
                class="style3">[43]</span></a></sup><span class="style3"> ensuring that 
            there is a clear disincentive to admit such patients. In the United States, laws 
            exist to ensure patients receive care in life-threatening emergency situations 
            regardless of the patient&#39;s ability to pay.</span><sup id="cite_ref-44" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-44"><span 
                class="style3">[44]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style5">
            <font size="3">As the quality of health care has increasingly become an issue 
            around the world, hospitals have increasingly had to pay serious attention to 
            this matter. Independent external assessment of quality is one of the most 
            powerful ways to assess this aspect of health care, and </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital_accreditation" 
                title="Hospital accreditation"><font size="3">hospital accreditation</font></a><font 
                size="3"> is one means by which this is achieved. In many parts of the world 
            such accreditation is sourced from other countries, a phenomenon known as </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_healthcare_accreditation" 
                title="International healthcare accreditation"><font size="3">international 
            healthcare accreditation</font></a><font size="3">, by groups such as </font>
            <a class="new" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Accreditation_Canada&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" 
                title="Accreditation Canada (page does not exist)"><font size="3">
            Accreditation Canada</font></a><font size="3"> from </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canada" title="Canada"><font size="3">
            Canada</font></a><font size="3">, the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_Commission" 
                title="Joint Commission"><font size="3">Joint Commission</font></a><font 
                size="3"> from the USA, the </font>
            <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trent_Accreditation_Scheme" 
                title="Trent Accreditation Scheme"><font size="3">Trent Accreditation Scheme</font></a><font 
                size="3"> from Great Britain, and Haute Authorité de santé (HAS) from 
            France.</font></p>
        <h2 class="style4">
            <span id="Buildings" class="style3">Buildings</span></h2>
        <h3 class="style4">
            <span id="Architecture" class="style3">Architecture</span></h3>
        <div class="thumb tright">
        </div>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style3">Modern hospital buildings are designed to minimise the 
            effort of medical personnel and the possibility of contamination while 
            maximising the efficiency of the whole system. Travel time for personnel within 
            the hospital and the transportation of patients between units is facilitated and 
            minimised. The building also should be built to accommodate heavy departments 
            such as radiology and operating rooms while space for special wiring, plumbing, 
            and waste disposal must be allowed for in the design.</span><sup 
                id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-45"><span 
                class="style3">[45]</span></a></sup></p>
        <p class="style5">
            <font size="3">However, the reality is that many hospitals, even those 
            considered &#39;modern&#39;, are the product of continual and often badly managed growth 
            over decades or even centuries, with utilitarian new sections added on as needs 
            and finances dictate. As a result, Dutch architectural historian </font>
            <a class="new" 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Cor_Wagenaar&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" 
                title="Cor Wagenaar (page does not exist)"><font size="3">Cor Wagenaar</font></a><font 
                size="3"> has called many hospitals:</font></p>
        <dl>
            <dd class="style4">
                <i><span class="style3">&quot;... built catastrophes, anonymous institutional 
                complexes run by vast bureaucracies, and totally unfit for the purpose they have 
                been designed for ... They are hardly ever functional, and instead of making 
                patients feel at home, they produce stress and anxiety.&quot;</span><sup 
                    id="cite_ref-ODE_46-0" class="reference"><a 
                    href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-ODE-46"><span 
                    class="style3">[46]</span></a></sup></i></dd>
        </dl>
        <p class="style4">
            <span class="style3">Some newer hospitals now try to re-establish design that 
            takes the patient&#39;s psychological needs into account, such as providing more 
            fresh air, better views and more pleasant colour schemes. These ideas harken 
            back to the late eighteenth century, when the concept of providing fresh air and 
            access to the &#39;healing powers of nature&#39; were first employed by hospital 
            architects in improving their buildings.</span><sup id="cite_ref-ODE_46-1" 
                class="reference"><a 
                href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hospital#cite_note-ODE-46"><span 
